        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>\noindent{\it Sensitivity:} To calculate the sensitivity, we
used the built in exposure time calculator in the ALMA Observing Tool at 688 GHz with the full 7.5 GHz bandwidth per
polarization to calculate the time required to reach 10$\sigma$
on the brightest flux prediction of the source or 5$\sigma$ for
the faintest prediction (the prediction range is shown in Table 1).

\noindent{\it Imaging:}
It would be scientifically compelling to obtain spatially resolved measure- ments of the dust distribution within the SN host and particularly at the location of the SN Ia. However, the exposure time requirements are prohibitively expensive, requiring &gt; 100 hrs per source. In Cycle 1, with the available ALMA sensitivity, we only aim to measure the integrated far-infrared continuum from the host galaxy. The galaxies have a radius of &lt; 1′′ in the Hubble/ACS optical images and will remain unresolved in the compact configuration. 
We adopt an LO frequency of 688 GHz to obtain the best opacity at Band 9.

\noindent{\it Correlator setup:} Since the goal is to constrain the
far-infrared luminosity with high precision ($\sim$10\%), the ALMA band has been
chosen to be as close to the peak of the far-infrared SED as possible;
this corresponds to Band 9 which samples 200 microns in the rest frame for
the majority of the SN hosts in the sample.
At Band 9 the atmospheric
opacity is highly variable and we appreciate that the observations are demanding.
We choose the best part of the atmospheric
window (based on the spectral visualizer in the OT) and tune to a LO =
688 GHz.  The single continuum selection sets up all 4 basebands in
the TDM mode in the upper sideband covering the frequency range from
676--684 GHz.  There are no strong atmospheric absorption lines in
this region which should greatly help our continuum sensitivity and
ability to obtain a clean  map with the desired S/N.

We investigated the possibility of undertaking
these observations in another band (e.g. Band 7) where atmospheric
conditions are better. However, the steep decline in
flux density along the Rayleigh-Jeans tail of the dust emission as well as the larger uncertainty
in extrapolating to a far-infrared luminosity excluded that possibility.

\noindent{\it Bandpass Accuracy:} There is no special need for additional bandpass accuracy.

\noindent{\it Schedule and Timing constraints:}None

\noindent{\it ``User-defined" calibration:}
None

\noindent{\it Data Rate:} Safely within limits
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
