    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>One of the largest sources of uncertainty in
the dark energy equation of state w(z) derived from SNe Ia arises from the uncertainty in deriving the peak intrinsic luminosity of the SNe. This is primarily due to
incorrect reddening corrections from our ignorance of the host galaxy dust properties. We propose a
pilot study where we utilize the extraordinary sensitivity of ALMA to obtain
observations of the thermal dust continuum at 450 micron of 3 z~1 Type Ia SNe host galaxies. Simultaneous fits to the multi-wavelength photometry of the host will provide robust measures
of the dust attenuation curve
in the host, parameterized as R_{V}. The product of R_{V} and the color excess E(B-V) derived from the SN light curve, will 
yield the true line of sight extinction to each of the SNe. This will reduce
the uncertainty in their true peak luminosity by a factor of two. The constraints on R_{V}
from these three SNe hosts will be extended to derive accurate reddening corrections
to all the other high-z SN light curves which will be a crucial stepping stone
towards reducing the systematic uncertainties in w(z) from Type Ia SNe.
</prp:abstract>
